name: Machine Learning Coding Challenge - Women Who Code X Outco
description:
Please REGISTER for the event here: https://us02web.zoom.us/webinar/register/2016098130163/WN_KUkygQ4KTrCj3A7Dp6niBg

Are you looking to ace your next software engineering role? Have you found it challenging to answer Kaggle's Challenges?

During this hands-on workshop Jordi Frank, a NASA Datanaut and Machine Learning Coach, will walk you through how to solve a Kaggle challenge. We will focus on Computer vision.

Who should attend:
Everyone is welcome!

About Outco

Outco is a 4-week job accelerator built specifically for software engineers. We’ve helped 2,000+ software developers through the hurdles of the job search. Do you know of any software engineers currently on the job hunt? If so, please have them join us at an Outco info session: https://www.outco.io/info-session-signup

Here is a video that summarizes the service that Outco provides: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=r-JCJfwKKlw&feature=youtu.be

Anyone who would like to join Outco, here is the referral link: https://www.outco.io/wwc

‚è∞ Agenda

6:30 PM – Welcome/ Announcements, Icebreaker
7:05 – 7:30 PM – Outco: Solving Coding Challenges
7:30 – 8:00 PM – Q&A, Networking

üë©üèΩ‍üíª About Women Who Code

Women Who Code (WWCode) is dedicated to providing an empowering experience for everyone who participates in or supports our community. Our events are intended to inspire women to excel in technology careers, and anyone who is there for this purpose is welcome. Because we value the safety and security of our members and strive to have an inclusive community, we do not tolerate harassment of members or event participants in any form. This Code of Conduct was created to clearly define what we mean by a harassment-free experience, so that our community and those who support it are clear about our intent and have access to procedures for addressing issues, should they arise.

Please read and abide by our Code of Conduct (https://github.com/WomenWhoCode/guidelines-resources/blob/master/code_of_conduct.md)

name: Women's Ruby Study Group: Let's learn Ruby together
description:
Overview

WWCode SF is working in collaboration with WWCode Tokyo and WWCode Toronto to bring together this study group as a community to learn and support Ruby.

We're a group of women who want to learn Ruby together. We welcome people of all levels. Beginners are especially encouraged. You move at your own pace in this group, so it doesn't matter if you are a fast or slow learner, or if you attend every week.

üéü HOW TO ACCESS THIS EVENT üéü

‚ö†Ô∏è This event is entirely over Slack! We will not have a video call for this event!

If you are already a member of WWCode Slack (https://wwcode.slack.com), just meet us on the channel #ruby-study-group at the time of this event!

If you are not a member of WWCode Slack yet, register on this meetup page and you will have access to the remote event link. The link is an invitation to our Slack group.

If you cannot access Slack or can't find the group channel, DM Aditi Lonhari or Tutti Quintella here on Meetup and we'll help you.

üë©üèª‍üíª HOW TO PREPARE FOR THIS STUDY SESSION üë©üèª‍üíª

You can choose what or how you will study ahead of time if you already have some ideas. We have a list of resources below as well to help you. Make sure you set up your local environment beforehand as well (steps below).

We will guide beginners to get your environment setup in this session and if we have enough time we will get started with the first exercise of the Ruby track Exercism.io (https://exercism.io/tracks/ruby).

To follow along with the exercises on Exercism with us, you can join our Exercism Team here: https://teams.exercism.io/teams/xLJwMZzyZZJ7qwVCbSFH6Jco/join

üíª SETUP YOUR LOCAL ENVIRONMENT üíª

Here are the steps of installing Exercism through CLI:
For MAC: Install exercism via Homebrew run:
$ brew update
$ brew install exercism

For Windows:
https://github.com/exercism/windows-installer/releases/tag/v1.5.3

Check the installed version with:
$ exercism version
It should be at least version 3.x

üõ† OTHER RESOURCES TO LEARN RUBY üõ†

Recommended resources for Ruby & Ruby on Rails (beginners):
- https://www.codecademy.com/learn/learn-ruby
- https://www.codecademy.com/learn/learn-rails
- https://guides.rubyonrails.org/ (Highly recommended)

You can find more here https://www.womenwhocode.com/resources?query=ruby

If you are more advanced, you can also work on whatever you like or jump in to help beginners.

üìå CODE OF CONDUCT ‚ö†Ô∏è

name: Women's Javascript Study Group: Intro to CSS
description:
If you are looking for study materials, we will be progressing through these online lessons together on wwcode.slack.com on the #sf-js-study-group channel. (If you don't have access, DM Aditi or Elaine on meetup.com a few days before, and we'll send you an invite.) We will not be using Zoom. If you're more advanced, work on whatever you like or jump in to help beginners.

Candice is hosting today's session. Topic for today is -
Intro to CSS Tutorial: https://www.codecademy.com/learn/learn-css

We strongly recommend starting the tutorials *before* the event, so that you can come to the study group with questions. Private Message Aditi with your email address a few days before the event if you still need slack access. This is a chat-only event, no Zoom.

Overview

We're a group of women who want to learn JavaScript together. We welcome people of all levels. Beginners are especially encouraged. You move at your own pace in this group, so it doesn't matter if you are a fast or slow learner, or if you attend every week. Meet us on wwcode.slack.com on the #sf-js-study-group channel. If you don't have access, DM Aditi or Elaine on meetup.com a few days before, and we'll send you an invite.

Format

We generally start introductions around 6:00pm and then work on coding problems or projects, independently or with others. Although the focus is on JavaScript, we also cover closely related topics such as HTML and CSS and other web technologies.

There will typically be more experienced coders available to help beginners with what they are stuck on.

(The only tools you need to start using JavaScript are a web browser and optionally a simple text editor or code editor.)

name: Algorithms & Interview Prep - Sorting and Searching (Whiteboarding Practice)
description:
Hi coders,

This event will be held remotely via Zoom. When you RSVP, the Zoom link will be available on this meetup page.

Requirements:
At minimum you will need a Zoom account. For the best experience, please aim to have a webcam, microphone, and an additional monitor if you have one. Also, if you like to draw and diagram, consider having a blank piece of paper and marker, or a whiteboard, that can be visible to your webcam.
To share your code, be prepared to screen-share, or collaborate through a google doc or repl.it.

To participate, please do the following:
1. Signup for a Zoom account: https://zoom.us/signup
2. Download the Zoom Client for Meetings: https://zoom.us/download#client_4meeting

Optional:
3. Create a Repl.it account: https://repl.it/signup
4. Create a free Leetcode account: https://leetcode.com/accounts/signup/

See our GitHub repo for study resources, example code, and practice problems:
https://github.com/WomenWhoCode/wwcsf-algos

Stay safe and healthy,
WWCSF

**************
Agenda
**************

6:30 - Welcome from event leads and mentors

6:45 - Introduce and discuss that night's topic
